a pivot through much of the first half of July.\n\nThe structure story on the daily timeframe is one of gradual, grinding recovery. After the sharp sell-off that took EUR/JPY from the 185.80s down to 183.14 between 21 and 24 June, buyers stepped in with conviction and the cross spent the following fortnight rebuilding. The sequence of higher lows from 25 June through to 14 July is notable \u2014 each daily close edged higher, culminating in a push to 186.02 on 15 July, the highest print in the observed window. Since that peak, the daily candles have been remarkably tight, with closes clustered between 185.76 and 185.93, suggesting the market is digesting those gains rather than surrendering them. The desk's bullish read is underpinned by this consolidation character; dips have been shallow and sellers have not been able to generate sustained downside momentum.\n\nThe key zones are stacked just above current price. A prior reaction zone sits at 185.99, which has registered four touches and represents the most significant near-term ceiling. Above that, structure resistance at 186.22 marks the level that would need to give way to open up a more meaningful extension. To the downside, structure support at 185.10 is the level that would materially challenge the bullish read \u2014 a daily close beneath there would suggest the recovery from June lows has stalled in a more meaningful way.\n\nOn the H1 chart, the intraday picture is one of tight, orderly consolidation. The dramatic spike to 186.20 and subsequent flush to 185.27 during the 04:00 UTC candle stands out as an outlier \u2014 likely a thin-market liquidity event \u2014 and price has since settled back into the 185.60\u2013185.82 corridor. Hourly closes have been consistent and the range is narrowing, which often precedes a directional resolution. The 185.82 structure resistance on the hourly is the immediate ceiling to watch.\n\nToday's calendar is light for this cross. German PPI for the month was released at 02:00 UTC with a low-impact designation, and given the muted reaction seen in the hours following, it has not materially shifted the narrative. Absent any surprise risk-event headlines from Tokyo or Frankfurt, volatility is likely to remain contained through the European session.\n\nThe bullish read would be challenged on a sustained break and close beneath the 185.10 structure support zone. Conversely, a clean hourly close above 185.99 would be consistent with the scenario where the consolidation resolves to the upside toward the 186.22 area.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}